---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import { webForgeUrl } from '../../data/products';
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Web Forge"
  eyebrow="Products"
  description="The browser edition of AgentKitForge — nothing to install, your kits available from any device."
>
  <p>
    Web Forge is the browser-based edition of AgentKitForge, at
    <a href={webForgeUrl}>webapp.forge.agentkitproject.com</a>. It runs the same
    <code>@agentkitforge/core</code> engine as the desktop app, so validation, packaging,
    and export produce identical results. Nothing to install — sign in and start building.
  </p>

  <h2>What you need</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>A modern browser (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, or Edge).</li>
    <li>A free AgentKitProject account — Web Forge is auth-gated (unlike the desktop app).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step by step</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Open <a href={webForgeUrl}>Web Forge</a> in your browser.</li>
    <li>Sign in with your AgentKitProject account via the WorkOS-powered login page.</li>
    <li>You land on <strong>My Kits</strong> — kits you own plus Market favorites.</li>
    <li>Build a new kit, use an existing one (Run / Chat), import a kit, package/export, install to local agent targets, or submit to Market.</li>
    <li>Your kits and favorites are stored in your account and sync across every browser and device.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Sections</h2>
  <p>
    Web Forge mirrors the desktop workflow: <strong>My Kits</strong>, <strong>Build</strong>,
    <strong>Use / Run / Chat</strong>, <strong>Import</strong>,
    <strong>Package / Export</strong>, <strong>Install Targets</strong>,
    <strong>Submit to Market</strong>, <strong>Settings</strong>, and <strong>About</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2>Free-tier quota</h2>
  <p>
    Web Forge stores your kits server-side under a per-account quota. The default free
    tier is <strong>25 kits</strong> and <strong>250&nbsp;MB</strong> of total storage,
    with a <strong>10&nbsp;MB</strong> per-file cap. A usage indicator shows how much of
    your quota you're using.
  </p>
  <div class="docs-note">
    <strong>Note.</strong> Quota limits are operator-configurable (the self-hosted build
    can override them via environment variables), so a self-hosted instance may differ
    from the hosted defaults above.
  </div>

  <h2>Desktop vs Web Forge</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Desktop is local-first and works with no account; Web Forge requires sign-in.</li>
    <li>Web Forge keeps everything in sync across devices via your account.</li>
    <li>Kits built in either can be exported and imported in the other — same package format.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
